segments.text: William's years, what were the major accomplishments, the major changes?
Of all the changes that I saw, what were the major changes?
Well, of course, on Rudder, in Rudder's time, I'd have to rank the coeducation military, non-military, as the primary changes there.
One other minor change which goes unnoticed I think sometimes is the amount of money we spent on making the whole campus wheelchair accessible.
Not much was said about that, but I watched that.
It was interesting.
Especially watching the academic buildings where
They went to great pains to build a ramp that had exactly the same architecture that the building involved.
I thought that was the highest sensibility on the map.
That's the rudder years.
I see that as being really... What about the Williams years?
Williams years...
Now somebody else had to start, just below him, start pulling the academic strings and making academia more visible, more respectable, and everything like that.
Who do you think did that?
I have to give him credit, but I'm not sure.
It may have even started down the rudder.
but I know Rudder is the one who appointed Bob Logan.
He said, you get all the stuff on the whole campus that has to do with scholarship in one place, and you do it now.
Not a bunch of deans do it, you do it.
That started there in his, probably his last couple of years or so.
Then I'd have to say Williams probably continued that way again.
Because that has been a,
been a watermark for the university.
I take people in and show them those plaques in the student center, and the number of endowed scholarship, they just gobble it up.
I think the Rutter Tower, which is built after Rutter, of course, and that complex there is a major event.
That ball, that may have started going before,
but it was finished in his administration and began to be used, and I think that furnished sort of a focal point for a lot of stuff.
But I don't really know any specific incidents about Williams' time as much as I know about Rudder's time.
It's more spectacular, I guess, than his, but there just seemed to be a general atmosphere
a pervasive academic atmosphere which was in those last years there.
Did you have any feel about any changes in student quality?
Oh yeah, we saw that.
Once again, that started in Rudder's years, but was enhanced down the line there.
in the counseling center, counseling and testing center back in the old days.
And we had charge of doing all the testing on the campus.
When I came in 61, they were not using the SAT or the ACT tests.
They were using the old American College of Education, Council of Education test, which was completely outdated and everything.
But they're using it because of their system of pre-week enrollment.
freshman week there, when they brought everybody in and gave them the test all in one pile and got the test results out and the advising done all in one week's time.
Come out of that freshman, even with corporate and stuff like that.
And they couldn't get, as I understand it, they couldn't get Educational Testing Service to go along with that.
So, for the fall of 62,
We got them to do, we did what they call a validation study of the SAT and had 2,000 students that year come in.
We took the SAT and ran the norms, compared to the national norm and all stuff like that.
Then the next year the board voted to require the SAT.
Our enrollment dropped to 1,300.
Everybody scared of the test, and everybody wanted to come where it wasn't required.
And we got our base norm that year.
And from that year on, it went up steadily from then on.
And the academic, it's hard to put your finger on what caused the improvement.
Maybe it took five or six years for that to really sink in.
kind of thing.
That we were really a class act from now on.
Funny thing, they did the same thing with the graduate school.
I don't know whether I ever told you this or not.
We administered the GRE to two years of graduating seniors.
Paid for it ourselves.
They paid for it.
It was called Institutional Administration.
And it was before we started requiring the GRE.
And we ran those norms, and it was so interesting because the university level of achievement, the verbal score was highest in the Department of History.
The math score was highest in the whole college of engineering at the figures.
But the highest department in the whole place on the Achievement Test, not the Aptitude Test, but the Achievement Test was the Department of Economics.
Did you know that?
I knew.
95th percentile rank on national norms.
How good.
Al Chalk had done his work well.
The lowest department was mathematics.
Fifth percentile rank on national norms.
And how important mathematics is to a science and engineering institution.
Well, they'd been teaching.
He's doing mathematics for years.
Well, see Rudder and the boy Rudder, I have to give him credit for this, because he found the money to give a lot of money to math and brought in some high-powered math people.
I don't remember their names right now, some of them weren't so hot, but they were used to academia and they got a big pay for a year or two to put their course on a video tape.
really successful.
And, but guess who he gave a lot of money to also?
The best department, Al Chong.
Got a lot of money for him.
And that's when it started going up.
But it takes a few years for that to seep on down and take effect only down in the Williams years, I think.
All right, now then in 1970 Dr. Williams replaces Rutter.
Then in 1976 Dr. Williams has a heart attack, almost fatal, not quite, replaced by Dr. Miller.
Who was the dean in education following Hubert?
Following Hubert was
Corrigan.
He didn't get here till 80 because I was the chairman of the committee that selected him.
Well, Limbacher was interim dean after Hubert.
Okay.
And they selected another dean at that time.
My mind's blank right now.
All right, does Hubert, Hubert becomes chancellor in the late 70s?
Yeah.
Okay, so maybe, maybe.
You said you became chancellor the same year that Miller was president.
Yeah, all right, and you remain active until you retire what year?
Okay, let's talk about Dean Carrigan then.
Describe him as dean.
Thorough scholar, and he was good for the college.
He didn't, he brought a national reputation with him.
And he immediately attracted the attention of the governor, who put him on the governor's special committee.
And he's got some tales to tell about that.
You may want to talk to him about that.
But he was the only educator on that whole committee of 25 people.
And Ross Perot was up in all these coattails all the time.
But he had some interesting tales to tell there.
Really, I believe he was.
I can't recall the dean before Dean Cardin.
He stayed nine years, didn't he?
Did he relate well to the education and statewide?
Statewide, as far as I know, he related well with them.
All right, at the time you retired then, where would you have placed Texas A&M's education program in the state, qualitatively?
That's a toughie.
I was minimally involved in teacher training, but I had an interest in it all the time.
I taught one course over there, adolescent psychology, all the time.
I didn't have a chance to really talk with other people at other institutions.
I have to go a little bit on reputation there, but I think we were better than Texas Tech and North Texas and San Marcos and others.
Commerce and Huntsville come up pretty high on my books.
University of Houston, not so well.
I didn't think their teacher prep down there was all that good.
But that's what I hear from it.
All right, what about UT?
Where were we compared to Austin?
Equal to or better.
Oh, OK.
So we, in your opinion, we were clearly one of the best, if not the best.
Okay.
Texas Tech had a strange system out there.
I never understood exactly what it was.
They refused to have departments.
They called them areas of emphasis out there.
And I didn't hear much out of that, good or bad.
But I always wondered how they got by with departing from the usual structure that we have and working within the system.
Let's look back.
Can you think of any, in hindsight, any mistakes that were made of action or inaction?
Here.
Yes.
Here.
Action or inaction.
There were things we did that turned out not to be
well-advised are things that we failed to do that we could have done.
I didn't think the consortium finally faded from the scene, just like performance-based education.
The consortium between the local school superintendent, the Texas University, and the
education service centers.
I thought that wasn't entirely our doing.
But I thought that idea was not so hot.
And areas of omission.
Are there some things we've just simply failed to... Well, partly from personal experience
And this little project I did on going out and evaluating what they thought, well, not enough classroom management, how to handle tough kids.
I had an Aggie come back to school from East Houston after having taught here in East Houston in seventh grade.
And she was a battle fatigue case.
They put her into a seventh grade classroom, little slums down there.
didn't give her any support, and so I think the lack of preparation for the real world of teaching is where I think they've fallen short, may still be falling short.
They teach them to go out, yes, into a nice small size, middle size, western rural area.
Don't have a lot of racial, social upheaval going on.
They do all right out there, but
If we're supposed to be preparing for East Dallas, South Dallas, and East Houston, I think we're failing there.
People that you now, as you look back on, that you would want to pat them on the back if you could?
John Barker.
Why?
Because he said, I'm willing to serve anywhere that anybody asks me.
I'll do it until I drop it.
He never, and because at certain crucial moments in faculty meetings, this man spoke up and said the things that some of us didn't have the guts to stand up and say.
And he was in your department?
Yeah, educational psychology.
Okay.
Yeah.
And he'd been there since the year before I came.
He took a full-time teaching job.
Which, by the way, I had also interviewed for that job and decided I would not take it.
I wasn't ready yet.
And Frank Hubert interviewed me.
Who else in addition to Berker that you would pat on the back, commend?
I think, unsung, Chris Borland.
He went on to be dean at UT San Antonio.
He doesn't get much credit for doing what he did here.
I'm not, I don't have to mention Williams and Rutter anymore.
I'm talking about other people who gave their whole life to this place and really need a pat on the back for it.
I think Chris Gromlin did, before he died.
Walter Varble.
He was in psychology?
He was in psychology, but he taught the education for me, just like everybody else.
I have to tell you a little bit about him.
This illustrates some past history that I wasn't here to observe, but I know about it because Varble told me all that, and the way things came about.
He was brought here in 1939 to head the psychology department.
Brand new PhD out of Kansas.
But before they got into reorganization, things were going a little bit slow then in war camp.
So he ended up teaching algebra and trigonometry throughout the war to ASTP people.
And then the president, after the war, was not in favor of psychology.
So we didn't have a psychology department.
Well, finally, they got preparatory to becoming a college of education, a college of liberal arts.
They decided to form a department of psychology, apart from department of educational psychology, or department of education, it was then.
Split the two.
So they did a national search for a department head.
Barman, in 1965,
as long as that, a few 25 years after he was chairman of the search committee.
They brought three people to the campus and they all turned it down.
Then the university, the board, whoever.
Well, Dr. Barber, how about you be the department head?
He told them to go to hell.
And to their everlasting shame,
misfortune they got Clesson Martin.
I'd have to go off camera before I talk very much about Clesson Martin.
He didn't do the university any good, really.
That's a long story.
Let's see, any staff people that you would want to pat on the back, special folks?
Yeah, I'd say Austin Curley.
Leading question, why?
Well, same reason he served, because somebody said do it.
He was the man on the spot and they said do it.
But he was putting in another possible situation when they
They'd take a master's degree guy and give him a position which had been held by a dean and decimate the college.
And he stayed and kept it together for 15 years after that.
And did some of the good things we just talked about, the testing program and stuff like that.
And he served on the committee for, did I know them?
of the Rutter Tower and all that stuff.
He was on the study committee that did that.
Yeah, I'd say Austin, they made him Emeritus, Emeritus Director of Counseling and Testing Center.
I don't know whether that includes being Emeritus in the department or not, but at least they kept the hat to him for that.
Let me think about that for a minute.
I should have asked quite ago, do you remember any change in manner or style of classes with women now in the class and or minority students?
Do you remember any incidents?
Yes.
Peggy was going to school when, and you may want to interview her some other time on that, she was in class with, before women were admitted.
And there was some minor harassment involved there in the language lab and stuff like that.
Nothing you really put your finger on, but it was obvious that they still were a good Aggie boy to do that kind of thing.
Yeah.
Do you remember any racial incidents of any sort?
No racial incidents.
There's some subtle attitudes, which I saw from time to time on faculty and students' parts.
You weren't, by chance, teaching a summer session that first summer that black students were enrolled?
No.
No, it wasn't.
Because I knew nothing about that going to happen right then until the announcement at the end of the first day of classes that that day black students had attended class.
And I never heard of a single incident at all.
I heard it was only positive.
Art, do you agree with me this way?

In those years before coeducation and integration, I felt that there was not any divisiveness in the student body over national background or anything that you were either an Aggie or you weren't an Aggie, that your nickname might indicate your ancestry.
But that was just part of the fact that faculty members had a nickname too.
Austin Curley told me that as a student here in 35, he had two Mexican-American school roommates.
Didn't make a big difference to him.
That's the impression I have.
In fact, he still keeps up with some of those people.
Were there still nicknames for faculty in education when you got here?
What were some of them?
I didn't know.
I didn't know what they were.
I knew about screaming out.
But I didn't hear any nicknames over our way.
There weren't any over there?
There must not have been, or I wouldn't have heard of them.

let's see now a while ago we were you didn't have think of any decisions of omission omission during these years omission which they should have done and I should have done and now in hindsight I get the impression this I don't know from personal observation but
The regular military faculty, I think, I get the impression that they did not do all they needed to do to help either integration or core education.
Anyway, over there, or core education.
That's my impression of it.
They all, service academies all did it before us.
and been announced as national policy from way back.

And being a part of a major institution, I thought even though they were most of them Aggies and they wanted to uphold their Aggie traditions, it seems to me that they could have done more than they did over there.
All right, we're getting close to the end now.
Any anecdotes you want to share?
I'll think of them after you leave.
I reserve the right to tell you after this.
What are some of your favorite Aggie stories?
I guess one of them, while I was still at Baylor, we had a basketball game on campus before the students came back to campus up there.
And Aggies do seem to do the fucking place, even in the holidays, to see the baseball game.
This must have been mid-50s, somewhere back in there.
And they had a riot over at the gymnasium.
I mean, of course, I was the dorm director living on the campus, and me and the other director peeled out of there and went over to the gymnasium and started trying to close the park.
And I hear somebody slugging somebody else, and one said, hey, don't hit me, I'm an Aggie too.
He couldn't tell who was who.
He said, I'm an Aggie too, don't hit me.
That's the honest truth.
That happened out there in front of the gymnasium on the campus of Baylor.
We had the Baylor students guarding the campus up there from the Aggies before they bailed.
And they had that game every year.
And they built fires on the corners.
One carload of Aggies had been roughed up quite a bit.
We brought them into the apartment there and gave them coffee and settled them down and sent them on their way.
That was my first contact with one of the greater Aggies while I was still a player.
That's absurd.
Of course, all the time, you remember in those years, an Aggie with a uniform didn't have to have wheels.
He could hitchhike anywhere in the state of Texas and no problem.
And I've not yet had a single, in all the conversations I've had, I've not yet heard a single horror story of Aggie hitchhiking.
They all say it went well, went well.
Let's see, in class, some Aggie fun stories from class.
I'll have to take a rain check.
Aggie excuses.
Oh, Aggie excuses, yeah.
I've heard some of the better ones that overshadow all of mine from a daughter, Chris.
She shares all of her excuses with me these days.
So I'm completely, but I reserve, I want to come back and tell her.
Tell her she ought to put those on tape.
You know, just pick out the machine and put it.
Some letters.
Yes.
Oh, yes.
Yeah.
All right, you can butt in one time.
You'd been teaching Monday, Wednesday practice.
Yeah.
And suddenly you got assigned one Tuesday, Thursday.
Yeah.
And you went on Wednesday and forgot to go on Thursday.
And then didn't have a meeting, but something happened that you weren't there on Friday.
When you went back on Monday, you said, well, how long did you wait till I come?
And he was going to go into the joke about with an instructor, you wait 10 minutes, and with an assistant professor, 15, associate, 30, and a full professor, one hour.
He said, how long did you wait?
And a voice came up from the back saying, I've been here since then.
Oh, that's good.
That's good.
All right.
Then the last, what parts of the institution are dearest in your heart?
Oh, that's a tough one.
I guess...
I'd like to say it to the conductor, but I guess I can't say that.
I say that because I like the citizen-soldier idea so much.
That's the reason I almost give them the vote.
But I guess the feeling of camaraderie that I have seen in graduate students in my department is the most heartening thing I have seen.
It is different from other institutions.
In other words, a cohort group comes in, 10, 12 people in one year, and they stay together for life, just like the Aggies do.
They, in professional life afterwards, they're there.
And I think I have to give some credit to that, the continuity of the faculty.
We had the same five faculty members.
Who were they?
Roach, Riley, Pope, Barman, and Smith.
Y'all came about the same time.
All came about the same time, late 60s or early 70s.
And stayed?
Well, I'm nobody there now.
No, but all stayed pretty well until retirement.
All stayed for 20 years, yeah.
And in that time is when we had this camaraderie with the graduate students.
They would pass on their apartment to the next people to come in, just like the vet school does.
And they had a few bucks for somebody who needed help, money wise.
And they covered, sometimes not widely, for their fellow students from time to time.
Any extracurricular parts of the institution that are deep in your heart?
I like the athletics.
I like the, I think spectator sports, mass spectator sports serves a useful purpose, especially as practiced here.
You see, no other institution that I know of has the control of the student body as these students do.
The yell leaders here and the core here has control of the crowd and everything else.
It's a riot at other places.
Look at the international scene in hockey and stuff like that.
And by no means do we approach that in other schools here, but I think A&M is superb.
And if there's ever evidence of sort of undergrowth and undergirding of a custom, worthwhile custom, it's that that's been perpetuated.
